DeLillo, Victor Navasky, and Jennifer EganPays particular attention to the extraordinary novels of Doctorow in the last 20 years, including The Waterworks, City of God, and a set of his recent preoccupations: corporate and religious power, cognitive science, and media cultureThis book gathers a suite of newly commissioned, original essays on the work of E. L. Doctorow. It reframes our understanding of his oeuvre by engaging it in entirety, including the significant accomplishments of the late period. The book features chapters by prominent fiction writers and friends of Doctorow, such as Don DeLillo, Victor Navasky and Jennifer Egan and explores Doctorow’s novels and his diverse preoccupations: corporate and religious power, cognitive science and media culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aArch, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvery, Tamlyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzzopardi, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLillo, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgan, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Nathan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwon, Jieun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurgatroyd, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphet, Julian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMurphet, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavasky, Victor S., econtributor.4ctb4https